        String getId()
        Returns a stable, globally unique ID for this. In terms of Cyc-specific nomenclature, this Id is the compact, hl external ID for the underlying Cyc object. Generally the HL IDs of indexed terms #$CycLIndexedTerms are useful. Cyc can generate HL IDs for Sentences, Variables and Symbols.

      • isAtomic

        Boolean isAtomic()
        Is this a non-decomposable KbObject? This will return true for KbObjects that represent Cyc constants, Cyc variables, or Cyc symbols. It returns false for anything else. For atomic assertions, or ground atomic formula, use instanceof Fact.
        Returns:
        true if and only if this KbObject is not decomposable into other constituent KbObjects

      • isIndexical

        boolean isIndexical()
             throws SessionCommunicationException
        Is this object an indexical? I.e., it is an instance of #$IndexicalConcept?

        Indexicals are those terms which depend upon the occasion of use or the user. For example, consider words such as "I", "Now", or "Here". When I use the word "I," I am referring to myself, but when you use the word "I", you are referring to yourself. Similarly, "Now" denotes the moment in which the word is used, and "Here" refers to the location at which the word is used.

        An entity which is referenced by an indexical is known as a referent. For example, the referent of "Here" could be France, the City of Austin, the room that we're currently in, or whatever else the geographical context might be when the word is used. (See #$indexicalReferent in the Cyc KB.) The process of determining the referent for an indexical is known as resolving the indexical.

        Some indexicals can be resolved automatically by Cyc; for example, Cyc can automatically resolve #$Now-Indexical to the current time, #$TheUser to the current Cyclist (per SessionOptions.getCyclistName(), or #$TheCurrentHostName to the hostname of the Cyc server. Other indexicals must be ultimately resolved somehow by the external application; for example, Cyc doesn't have any rules for resolving an indexical like (TheNamedFn InformationStore "data source").

        In the case of queries, all of the indexicals in a query's sentence and context must be resolved in order for the query to be run. Cyc will handle any automatically resolvable indexicals (such as #$Now-Indexical), but all other indexicals must be resolved by the application; for example, (TheNamedFn InformationStore "data source") would need to be replaced with a specific instance of #$InformationStore. This can be accomplished by adding substitutions to a Query; for more information, see com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#setSubstitutions(java.util.Map) .

        Returns:
        whether the object is an indexical
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        See Also:
        resolveIndexical(), KbTerm.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), Sentence.getIndexicals(boolean), Sentence.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#setSubstitutions(java.util.Map), com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#addSubstitutions(java.util.Map), QuerySpecification.getSubstitutions()

      • isQuoted

        boolean isQuoted()
          throws KbTypeException,
                 CreateException
        Returns whether this is a quoted object; i.e., if it refers to the CycL object itself and not its meaning. For example, (#$Quote #$Plato) refers to the term #$Plato, and not to the philosopher.

        Refer to #$NoteAboutQuotingInCycL for a more detailed discussion of quoting.

        Returns:
        whether this is a quoted object
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException
        See Also:
        quote(), unquote(), toQuoted(), toUnquoted()

      • quote

        KbIndividual quote()
            throws KbTypeException,
                   CreateException
        Returns a quoted version of this object. E.g., this method would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from #$Plato. This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject. Calling this method on a quoted object will return a quoted object which is nested one level deeper; e.g., this method would return (#$Quote (#$Quote #$Plato)) from (#$Quote #$Plato). For a version of this method which won't further nest quoted objects, see toQuoted().

        See isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

        Returns:
        the quoted version of this object
        Throws:
        CreateException
        KbTypeException
        See Also:
        isQuoted(), unquote(), toQuoted(), toUnquoted()

      • unquote

        <O> O unquote()
       throws KbTypeException,
              CreateException
        Returns the object referred to by a quoted object. E.g., this method would return #$Plato from (#$Quote #$Plato). This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new object. This method will only remove one level of quoting; e.g., it would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from (#$Quote (#$Quote #$Plato)). If the object is not quoted, a KbTypeException will be thrown. For a version of this method which won't throw an exception for an unquoted object, and which will fully unquote nested quotes, see toUnquoted().

        See isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

        Type Parameters:
        O - expected return type of the unquoted object
        Returns:
        the unquoted version of this object
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException
        See Also:
        isQuoted(), quote(), toQuoted(), toUnquoted()

      • toQuoted

        KbIndividual toQuoted()
               throws KbTypeException,
                      CreateException
        Returns a quoted version of this object. This method is similar to quote(), but will return a reference to itself if the object is already quoted (as opposed to returning a nested version of the quoted object). E.g., this method would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from either #$Plato or (#$Quote #$Plato). This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject (or a reference to itself, if it's already quoted.)

        See isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

        Returns:
        the quoted version of this object, or this object if it is already quoted
        Throws:
        CreateException
        KbTypeException
        See Also:
        isQuoted(), quote(), unquote(), toUnquoted()

      • toUnquoted

        <O> O toUnquoted()
          throws KbTypeException,
                 CreateException
        Returns a fully-unquoted version of this object. This method is similar to unquote(), but will remove multiple levels of quoting if necessary, and will return a reference to itself if the object is not quoted. E.g., this method would return #$Plato from #$Plato, (#$Quote #$Plato), or (#$Quote (#$Quote #$Plato)). This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new object (or a reference to itself, if it's already fully unquoted.)

        See isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

        Type Parameters:
        O - expected return type of the unquoted object
        Returns:
        the unquoted version of this object, or this object if it is not quoted
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException
        See Also:
        isQuoted(), quote(), unquote(), toQuoted()

      • possiblyResolveIndexical

        <O> O possiblyResolveIndexical(Map<KbObject,Object> substitutions)
                        throws SessionCommunicationException,
                               KbTypeException
        Attempts to resolve the object from a substitutions map. If the object is an indexical and has a referent specified in the substitutions map, this method will return the referent object from the substitutions map; if the original object is not an indexical, it will simply return itself. Note that this method will not attempt to do any automatic resolution; see resolveIndexical() if you need that.

        This method is specifically intended to be called in large batch operations where some KbObjects may be indexicals and others may not, and to be chained with other methods like KbTerm.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), so it attempts to be a little more forgiving than #resolveIndexical(). For this reason, it will not throw an exception simply because the original object is not an indexical. However, it will throw an exception under any of the following conditions:

        • The object is not an indexical, but a referent is found in the substitutions map.
        • The object is an indexical which cannot be automatically resolved, and no referent is found in the substitutions map.
        • The referent provided by the substitutions map is the same as the original object.
        • The referent is not of the expected type.

        For a brief overview of indexicals, see isIndexical().

        Type Parameters:
        O - the referent's expected type
        Parameters:
        substitutions - the substitutions map
        Returns:
        the object's referent, or the object itself (if not an indexical)
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        KbTypeException - if the referent is not of the expected type
        See Also:
        resolveIndexical()

      • resolveIndexical

        <O> O resolveIndexical()
                throws SessionCommunicationException,
                       KbTypeException,
                       CreateException
        If the object is an indexical, attempt to resolve it and return the appropriate referent. For example, if called on #$Now-Indexical, this method would return the current date and time. This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject. If the indexical cannot be automatically resolved, or if the KbObject is not an indexical, an exception will be thrown.

        For a brief overview of indexicals, see isIndexical().

        Type Parameters:
        O - the referent's expected type
        Returns:
        the indexical's referent for the current context
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        KbTypeException - if the object is not an indexical
        CreateException
        See Also:
        possiblyResolveIndexical(java.util.Map)

      • equalsSemantically

        boolean equalsSemantically(Object object)
        Does this represent the same object in the KB as object. This can return true even if the two objects being compared are of different classes, as long as they represent the same object in the KB. Ideally if factory methods are used to create KB API objects, it will ensure that the object returned will be of the tightest subclass possible, so object comparisons will work even when cast to super.
        Parameters:
        object - the object to compare against this
        Returns:
        true if the underlying CycObject is the same for two different KbObjects
